                     <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1635" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am in the employ of John and 
               <persName id="t18310217-165-person1636">
                  Robert 
                  Warner
               <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1636" type="surname" value="Warner"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1636" type="given" value="Robert"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1636" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , <rs id="t18310217-165-viclabel993" type="occupation">brass-founder</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-165-victim1634 t18310217-165-viclabel993"></join>s, <placeName id="t18310217-165-crimeloc994">Jewin-crescent</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-165-crimeloc994" type="placeName" value="Jewin-crescent"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-165-crimeloc994" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-165-off991 t18310217-165-crimeloc994"></join> - the prisoner was in their employ. On the 17th of January, in consequence of directions, I watched him, and about a quarter-past twelve o'clock I saw him take the copper out of the pan and put it into his pocket - it was old halfpence and pocket-pieces intended for melting; I told Mr. Handley.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-165-person1637">
                  JAMES 
                  WILLIAM HANDLEY
               <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1637" type="surname" value="WILLIAM HANDLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1637" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1637" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am foreman to Messrs. Warner. In consequence of what Milward said, I fetched the prisoner from the foundry into the counting-house, and told him he had something in his possession which did not belong to him - he said he had not; I said he had - he pulled out two halfpence; I said, "That will not do, I must have the rest" - he then pulled out 12 ozs. of small copper, said it was the first time, and he hoped I would let him go; I went with the officer to his lodging, and found a 1 lb., a 2 lbs., and a - lb. weight, and a piece of copper, which are masters'.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. STURGEON. Q. Is it unusual for men when melting to put money into their pockets? A. No, it is never allowed.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-165-person1638">
                  JOHN 
                  ANDREWS
               <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1638" type="surname" value="ANDREWS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1638" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1638" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I produce the copper, which was delivered to me.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-165-person1639">
                  JAMES 
                  WILLIAM HANDLEY
               <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1639" type="surname" value="WILLIAM HANDLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1639" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-165-person1639" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . This is the copper I delivered to the constable - we have a hundred and forty men in our employ.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Did you hold out any threat or promise to him? A. None at all - he has a wife and six children; I believe master had a fifteen years' character with him.</p>
               <p>JURY. Q. What did he earn a week? A. For the last twelve weeks he has earned 30s. a week.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 35.</p>
